x4freetext: Gamma-rays from the target are viewed by
a 25% detector with a resolution of 2 keV (FWHM) at
60Co lines and about 4.5 keV at 6 MeV and a 20%
detector with approximately the same resolution. For
both detectors the relative efficiency and energy
calibration was made relative to the reaction
35Cl(n,gamma) and with the radioactive sources 152Eu
and 133Ba for the low energy part.
Single gamma-ray and gamma-gamma coincidence
measurements.
Two single spectra were measured with both detectors
simultaneously, one in the energy range 0 - 2.4 MeV,
and another one between 0 and 7.2 MeV. By normalizing
the data of both spectra relative to the strongest
peak at 1026 keV a list of primary and secondary
gamma -rays in this reaction was made. The relative
intensities of the 183W spectra were converted into
absolute units using activation lines from the beta
of 187W to 187Re which were observed in the target as
contaminant lines during its irradiation.

x4freetext: The absolute intensities of 14 most reliable
secondary and 13 primary gamma-rays in combination
with the elemental partial gamma-ray production cross
sections of natural W were used to calculate the
value of the thermal neutron capture cross section on
182-W. The result was obtained by weighted average.
Elemental partial gamma-ray production cross sections
of natural W were obtained from ref.:
R.B.Firestone,Evaluated gamma-ray activation file
http://www-nds.iaea.org/pgaa/PGAAdatabase/reports/W/
